eland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1102–":"about 1102–Deceased","1102–Male":"1102–Deceased","1147–Female":"1147–Deceased","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1078–1103":"1078–1103","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","Abt 1102":"about 1102","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marsham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Marsham (Norfolk)."],"variants":[{"name":"Marshom","meanings":["English:  see  Marsham  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Marsham was born about 1102, in Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas De Marsham. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1102–":"umbes 1102–Surnud","1102–Male":"1102–Surnud","1147–Female":"1147–Surnud","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1078–1103":"1078–1103","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","Abt 1102":"umbes 1102","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1102–":"noin 1102–Kuollut","1102–Male":"1102–Kuollut","1147–Female":"1147–Kuollut","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1078–1103":"1078–1103","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","Abt 1102":"noin 1102","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1102–":"environ 1102–Décédé","1102–Male":"1102–Décédé","1147–Female":"1147–Décédée","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1078–1103":"1078–1103","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","Abt 1102":"environ 1102","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Richard Marsham est né environ 1102, à Marsham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Thomas De Marsham. Il a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille."},"de":{"Abt 1102–":"um 1102–Verstorben","1102–Male":"1102–Verstorben","1147–Female":"1147–Verstorben","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1078–1103":"1078–1103","1190":"1190","1149":"1149","Abt 1102":"um 1102","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Richard Marsham wurde um 1102 in Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, als Sohn von Thomas De Marsham geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn 